neutral','6.38'),(1103,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/rss-publishing','default',_binary 'Number of items in each feed','6.38'),(1104,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/rss-publishing','default',_binary 'Default number of items to include in each feed.','6.38'),(1105,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/rss-publishing','default',_binary 'Feed content','6.38'),(1106,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/rss-publishing','default',_binary 'Titles only','6.38'),(1107,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/rss-publishing','default',_binary 'Titles plus teaser','6.38'),(1108,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/rss-publishing','default',_binary 'Full text','6.38'),(1109,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/rss-publishing','default',_binary 'Global setting for the default display of content items in each feed.','6.38'),(1110,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'No vocabularies available.','6.38'),(1111,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'Edit term','6.38'),(1112,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'Add vocabulary','6.38'),(1113,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'The taxonomy module allows you to categorize your content using both tags and administrator defined terms. It is a flexible tool for classifying content with many advanced features. To begin, create a \'Vocabulary\' to hold one set of terms or tags. You can create one free-tagging vocabulary for everything, or separate controlled vocabularies to define the various properties of your content, for example \'Countries\' or \'Colors\'.','6.38'),(1114,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'Use the list below to configure and review the vocabularies defined on your site, or to list and manage the terms (tags) they contain. A vocabulary may (optionally) be tied to specific content types as shown in the <em>Type</em> column and, if so, will be displayed when creating or editing posts of that type. Multiple vocabularies tied to the same content type will be displayed in the order shown below. To change the order of a vocabulary, grab a drag-and-drop handle under the <em>Name</em> column and drag it to a new location in the list. (Grab a handle by clicking and holding the mouse while hovering over a handle icon.) Remember that your changes will not be saved until you click the <em>Save</em> button at the bottom of the page.','6.38'),(1115,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'The taxonomy module allows you to categorize content using various systems of classification. Free-tagging vocabularies are created by users on the fly when they submit posts (as commonly found in blogs and social bookmarking applications). Controlled vocabularies allow for administrator-defined short lists of terms as well as complex hierarchies with multiple relationships between different terms. These methods can be applied to different content types and combined together to create a powerful and flexible method of classifying and presenting your content.','6.38'),(1116,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'For example, when creating a recipe site, you might want to classify posts by both the type of meal and preparation time. A vocabulary for each allows you to categorize using each criteria independently instead of creating a tag for every possible combination.','6.38'),(1117,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'Type of Meal: <em>Appetizer, Main Course, Salad, Dessert</em>','6.38'),(1118,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'Preparation Time: <em>0-30mins, 30-60mins, 1-2 hrs, 2hrs+</em>','6.38'),(1119,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'Each taxonomy term (often called a \'category\' or \'tag\' in other systems) automatically provides lists of posts and a corresponding RSS feed. These taxonomy/term URLs can be manipulated to generate AND and OR lists of posts classified with terms. In our recipe site example, it then becomes easy to create pages displaying \'Main courses\', \'30 minute recipes\', or \'30 minute main courses and appetizers\' by using terms on their own or in combination with others. There are a significant number of contributed modules which you to alter and extend the behavior of the core module for both display and organization of terms.','6.38'),(1120,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'Terms can also be organized in parent/child relationships from the admin interface. An example would be a vocabulary grouping countries under their parent geo-political regions. The taxonomy module also enables advanced implementations of hierarchy, for example placing Turkey in both the \'Middle East\' and \'Europe\'.','6.38'),(1121,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'The taxonomy module supports the use of both synonyms and related terms, but does not directly use this functionality. However, optional contributed or custom modules may make full use of these advanced features.','6.38'),(1122,'/drupal-6.38/admin/content/taxonomy','default',_binary 'For more information, see the online handbook entry for <a href=\"@taxonomy\">Taxonomy module</a>.','6.38'),(1123,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/error-reporting','default',_binary 'Default 403 (access denied) page','6.38'),(1124,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/error-reporting','default',_binary 'This page is displayed when the requested document is denied to the current user. If unsure, specify nothing.','6.38'),(1125,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/error-reporting','default',_binary 'Default 404 (not found) page','6.38'),(1126,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/error-reporting','default',_binary 'This page is displayed when no other content matches the requested document. If unsure, specify nothing.','6.38'),(1127,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/error-reporting','default',_binary 'Write errors to the log','6.38'),(1128,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/error-reporting','default',_binary 'Write errors to the log and to the screen','6.38'),(1129,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/error-reporting','default',_binary 'Specify where Drupal, PHP and SQL errors are logged. While it is recommended that a site running in a production environment write errors to the log only, in a development or testing environment it may be helpful to write errors both to the log and to the screen.','6.38'),(1130,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/language','default',_binary 'Left to right','6.38'),(1131,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/language','default',_binary 'Code','6.38'),(1132,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/language','default',_binary 'English name','6.38'),(1133,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/language','default',_binary 'Native name','6.38'),(1134,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/language','default',_binary 'Direction','6.38'),(1135,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/site-maintenance','default',_binary 'Site status','6.38'),(1136,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/site-maintenance','default',_binary 'Online','6.38'),(1137,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/site-maintenance','default',_binary 'Off-line','6.38'),(1138,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/site-maintenance','default',_binary 'When set to \"Online\", all visitors will be able to browse your site normally. When set to \"Off-line\", only users with the \"administer site configuration\" permission will be able to access your site to perform maintenance; all other visitors will see the site off-line message configured below. Authorized users can log in during \"Off-line\" mode directly via the <a href=\"@user-login\">user login</a> page.','6.38'),(1139,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/site-maintenance','default',_binary 'Site off-line message','6.38'),(1140,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/site-maintenance','default',_binary 'Message to show visitors when the site is in off-line mode.','6.38'),(1141,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'The normal cache mode is suitable for most sites and does not cause any side effects. The aggressive cache mode causes Drupal to skip the loading (boot) and unloading (exit) of enabled modules when serving a cached page. This results in an additional performance boost but can cause unwanted side effects.','6.38'),(1142,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary '<strong class=\"ok\">Currently, all enabled modules are compatible with the aggressive caching policy.</strong> Please note, if you use aggressive caching and enable new modules, you will need to check this page again to ensure compatibility.','6.38'),(1143,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Page cache','6.38'),(1144,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Enabling the page cache will offer a significant performance boost. Drupal can store and send compressed cached pages requested by <em>anonymous</em> users. By caching a web page, Drupal does not have to construct the page each time it is viewed.','6.38'),(1145,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Caching mode','6.38'),(1146,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Normal (recommended for production sites, no side effects)','6.38'),(1147,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Aggressive (experts only, possible side effects)','6.38'),(1148,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary '0 sec','6.38'),(1149,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary '1 min','6.38'),(1150,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary '@count min','6.38'),(1151,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary '1 hour','6.38'),(1152,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Minimum cache lifetime','6.38'),(1153,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'On high-traffic sites, it may be necessary to enforce a minimum cache lifetime. The minimum cache lifetime is the minimum amount of time that will elapse before the cache is emptied and recreated, and is applied to both page and block caches. A larger minimum cache lifetime offers better performance, but users will not see new content for a longer period of time.','6.38'),(1154,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Page compression','6.38'),(1155,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'By default, Drupal compresses the pages it caches in order to save bandwidth and improve download times. This option should be disabled when using a webserver that performs compression.','6.38'),(1156,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Block cache','6.38'),(1157,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Enabling the block cache can offer a performance increase for all users by preventing blocks from being reconstructed on each page load. If the page cache is also enabled, performance increases from enabling the block cache will mainly benefit authenticated users.','6.38'),(1158,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Enabled (recommended)','6.38'),(1159,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Note that block caching is inactive when modules defining content access restrictions are enabled.','6.38'),(1160,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Bandwidth optimizations','6.38'),(1161,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary '<p>Drupal can automatically optimize external resources like CSS and JavaScript, which can reduce both the size and number of requests made to your website. CSS files can be aggregated and compressed into a single file, while JavaScript files are aggregated (but not compressed). These optional optimizations may reduce server load, bandwidth requirements, and page loading times.</p><p>These options are disabled if you have not set up your files directory, or if your download method is set to private.</p>','6.38'),(1162,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'Optimize CSS files','6.38'),(1163,'/drupal-6.38/admin/settings/performance','default',_binary 'This option can 